\n|\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 14th\n|\n|align=\"right\"| '''8'''\n|-\n! 43\n| [[Simon Emmerling]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 11th\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|align=\"right\"| '''7'''\n|-\n! 44\n| [[Lester Smerdon]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 12th\n|\n|\n|align=\"right\"| '''6'''\n|-\n! 44\n| [[Ray Ellis (racing driver)|Ray Ellis]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 12th\n|\n|align=\"right\"| '''6'''\n|-\n! 44\n| [[John Giddings (racing driver)|John Giddings]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 16th\n|align=\"right\"| '''6'''\n|-\n! 44\n| [[John White (racing driver)|John White]]\n|\n|\n|\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 20th\n|\n|\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 18th\n|\n|\n|\n|align=\"right\"| '''6'''\n|-\n! 48\n| [[Ken Mathews]]\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 13th\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|style=\"background:#cfcfff;\"| 18th\n|align=\"right\"| '''5'''\n|-\n! 49\n| [[Kevin Clark (racing driver)|Kevin Clark]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 14th\n|\n|\n|align=\"right\"| '''4'''\n|-\n! 50\n| [[Garry Willmington]]\n|style=\"background:#efcfff;\"| Ret\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 15th\n|\n|style=\"background:#efcfff;\"| Ret\n|align=\"right\"| '''3'''\n|-\n! 50\n| [[Wally Kramer]]\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 15th\n|align=\"right\"| '''3'''\n|-\n! 52\n| [[Darryl Hendrick]]\n|\n|\n|\n|style=\"background:#cfcfff;\"| 21st\n|\n|\n|style=\"background:#dfffdf;\"| 20th\n|\n|\n|\n|align=\"right\"| '''2'''\n|-  style=\"background:#f9f9f9; vertical-align:top;\"\n!valign=\"middle\"| Pos\n!valign=\"middle\"| Driver\n! style=\"width:2%;\"| Rd 1\n! style=\"width:2%;\"| Rd 2\n! style=\"width:2%;\"| Rd 3\n! style=\"width:2%;\"| Rd 4\n! style=\"width:2%;\"| Rd 5\n! style=\"width:2%;\"| Rd 6\n! style=\"width:2%;\"| Rd 7\n! style=\"width:2%;\"| Rd 8\n! style=\"width:2%;\"| Rd 9\n! style=\"width:2%;\"| Rd 10\n!valign=\"middle\"| Pts\n|}\n|valign=\"top\"|\n{{Motorsport driver results legend}}\n|}\n\n==See also==\n[[1986 Australian Touring Car season]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20020928161349/http://www.v8supercar.com.au/ Official V8 Supercar site] Contains historical ATCC information.\n\n{{Australian Touring Car Racing}}\n\n[[Category:Australian Touring Car Championship seasons]]\n[[Category:1986 in Australian motorsport|Touring Cars]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Australian English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Motorsport season\n|title = [[Australian Touring Car Championship]]\n|link = Australian Touring Car Championship\n|year = 1986\n}}\n\nThe '''1986 Australian Touring Car Championship''' was the 27th running of the [[Australian Touring Car Championship]]. It began on 2 March 1986 at [[Amaroo Park]] and ended on 13 July at [[Oran Park Raceway]] after ten rounds. This was the second ATCC to be run to the [[FIA]]'s international [[Group A]] [[Touring car racing|Touring Car]] Regulations.\n\n==Season Summary==\nThe championship was won by [[Auckland]] ([[New Zealand]]) resident [[Robbie Francevic]] driving a [[Volvo Dealer Team]] [[Volvo 240T]], the first time the championship had been won by a non-Australian resident and the first ATCC won by a [[turbocharged]] car. Francevic, who won Rounds 1, 2 and 4, defeated [[George Fury]] driving a [[Nissan Skyline DR30 RS]] who won Rounds 3, 5, 7, 8 and 10 of the series. Francevic's wins in the opening two rounds at [[Amaroo Park]] and [[Symmons Plains Raceway|Symmons Plains]] where when the [[Volvo]] team was still run by MPM, [[Mark Petch Motorsport]]. Following Francevic's Amaroo win, Petch and Bob Atkins, head of the Australian Volvo Dealer Council, announced the formation of the AVDT, Australian Volvo Dealer Team, and hired former HDT team manager John Sheppard to run the team on a day-to-day basis from Sheppard's Calder work shop. Contrary to what has been written in the past, Petch stayed involved as \"Team Principle\" until 10 July 1986, when he resigned over a disagreement with how Sheppard was managing the Team. The AVDT purchased MPM original 240T GpA car, and spares, which included a spare 240 GT body shell, which later became the basis for a new Australian built car, with all new parts and technical assistance from VMS. Francevic's [[1985 Australian Endurance Championship|1985 endurance]] co-driver and dual [[Australian Drivers' Championship|Australian Drivers' Champion]] [[John Bowe (racing driver)|John Bowe]] joining the team full-time for his first ATCC campaign, in the teams new second car, a RHD car ex RAS in Belgium, which arrived just in time for the 4th round of the ATCC at Adelaide International Raceway, were Bowe qualified on pole, and lead the race before engine issue's forced his retirement. Bowe repeated his first Championship Pole position performance at the 5th round of the Champion at Barbagallo Raceway, only to have to retire again from a substantial lead with more engine issues. [[Peter Brock]] won round 6 at [[Surfers Paradise International Raceway|Surfers Paradise]] in his new for 1986 [[Holden VK Commodore SS Group A]] (his last ATCC win until [[1989 Australian Touring Car Championship|1989]] and the last race win by a [[Holden Commodore]] until his win in Round 1, Heat 1 of the [[1992 Australian Touring Car Championship|1992 ATCC]]) while defending champion [[Jim Richards (race driver)|Jim Richards]] could only manage one win in his [[JPS Team BMW]] [[BMW E24|635 CSi]], winning Round 9 at [[Winton Motor Raceway|Winton]]. Richards had finished the race in second place behind Nissan team driver Gary Scott, but the Nissan was later disqualified for having oversize brake. Although the paperwork for the Nissan's new brakes had been put through, they had not yet been homologated which led to Scott's DQ.\n\nSeries regular [[Allan Grice]] missed the 1986 ATCC (he had also missed the [[1985 Australian Touring Car Championship|1985 championship]]) as he was racing his [[Roadways Racing|Les Small]] prepared Group A Commodore in the [[1986 European Touring Car Championship|1986 FIA Touring Car Championship]] ([[European Touring Car Championship|ETCC]]). Peter Brock missed some early rounds due to also racing his Commodore in Europe.\n\nWith the ATCC consisting of 10 rounds, many of the top level teams including the [[Holden Dealer Team]], [[Dick Johnson Racing]], JPS Team BMW and the [[Gibson Motorsport|Peter Jackson Nissan team]] all made loud noises during the year about the lack of prize money on offer for their efforts as the top drawing motorsport category in the country, especially as Group A racing had proven far more expensive than the old [[Group C (Australia)|Group C]] regulations (Peter Brock estimated that his [[Bathurst 1000|Bathurst]] winning Group C [[Holden VK Commodore|Commodore]] of [[1984 James Hardie 1000|1984]] had cost around [[Australian dollar|AU$]]36,000 to build while his 1986 Group A Commodore had cost around $200,000, a cost increase of around 550%), with teams and drivers often racing for as little as $1,500 for a round win. Part of the problem for the teams was that due to Australia's size and the vast distance between the major cities where the race tracks were located, the prize money on offer usually did not even cover their transportation costs, let alone the cost of building, maintaining and racing the cars. Pressure was being put on the [[Confederation of Australian Motor Sport]] (CAMS) to come up with a series sponsor for future championships or they would risk smaller and smaller grids. CAMS rectified this from [[1987 Australian Touring Car Championship|1987]] by signing a multi-year sponsorship deal with [[Royal Dutch Shell|Shell]] who would provide some $275,000 in prize money.\n\n==Teams and drivers==\n[[File:Mustangnelson.jpg|thumb|right|Lawrie Nelson's Ford Mustang]]The following drivers and teams competed in the 1986 [[Australian Touring Car Championship]]. The series consisted of ten rounds of with one race per round.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n!Team\n!Car model\n!No\n!Driver\n|- \n| rowspan=3 | [[JPS Team BMW]]\n| [[BMW 635CSi]]\n| 1\n| {{flagicon|NZL}} [[Jim Richards (race driver)|Jim Richards]]\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | [[BMW 3 Series (E30)|BMW 325i]]\n| 23\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Garry Rogers]]\n|- \n| 25\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Tony Longhurst]]\n|- \n| Chickadee Racing\n| [[Holden VK Commodore SS Group A]]\n| 2\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Graeme Bailey]] \n|- \n| Graeme Crosby\n| Holden VK Commodore SS Group A\n| 2<br>6<br>20\n| {{flagicon|NZL}} [[Graeme Crosby]] \n|- \n| rowspan=2 | [[Mobil Holden Dealer Team]]\n| rowspan=2 | Holden VK Commodore SS Group A\n| 3\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[John Harvey (motorsport)|John Harvey]]\n|- \n| 05\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Peter Brock]]<br>{{flagicon|NZL}} [[Neal Lowe]]\n|-\n| Peter McLeod\n| Holden VK Commodore SS Group A\n| 4\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Peter McLeod]] \n|- \n| rowspan=2 | [[Volvo Dealer Team]]\n| rowspan=2 | [[Volvo 240T]]\n| 4<br>44\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[John Bowe (racing driver)|John Bowe]]\n|-\n| 10\n| {{flagicon|NZL}} [[Robbie Francevic]]\n|- \n| rowspan=2 | Charlie O'Brien\n| rowspan=2 | BMW 635CSi\n| 7\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Charlie O'Brien (racing driver)|Charlie O'Brien]]\n|-  \n| 22\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Gregg Hansford]]\n|-\n| Terry Finnigan\n| Holden VK Commodore SS Group A\n| 8\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Terry Finnigan]]\n|- \n| Kevin Bartlett\n| [[Mitsubishi Starion]]\n| 9\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Kevin Bartlett (race driver)|Kevin Bartlett]] \n|- \n| rowspan=2 | [[Toyota Team Australia]]\n| [[Toyota Corolla GT AE86]]\n| 11\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Drew Price]]\n|-\n| [[Toyota Corolla FX-GT AE82]]\n| 16\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[John Smith (race driver)|John Smith]]\n|-\n| Garry Willmington Performance\n| [[Jaguar XJS]]\n| 12\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Garry Willmington]]\n|-\n| Simon Emmerling\n| BMW 635CSi\n| 12\n| {{flagicon|A